00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:11.360
Build It.

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.450
Canadian artist Aganetha Dyck collaborates
with bees to alter man-made objects.

00:00:16.450 --> 00:00:22.130
Honeybee Alterations takes things like porcelain
figurines in conjunction with the bees natural

00:00:22.130 --> 00:00:26.300
beeswax making process to create altered sculptures.

00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:30.740
And she uses the artwork to help illustrate
the delicate relationship between humans and

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:31.740
bees.

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:36.570
Daniel Rozin makes interactive mirrors out
of things like trash, fans, weaved material

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:38.110
and wooden pegs.

00:00:38.110 --> 00:00:43.140
The sculptures react in real time to the movements
in front of them using custom software and

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:44.430
video sensors.

00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:48.950
His installations have the ability to respond
to the specific presence of the viewer making

00:00:48.950 --> 00:00:51.100
them part of the piece itself.

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:54.390
Michelle Jewell creates one of a kind stuffed
animals.

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:59.590
Body parts are made from fleece material with
unique clothing made from upcycled and vintage

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:00.650
fabric.

00:01:00.650 --> 00:01:03.570
All of the toys are handsewn and stuffed.

00:01:03.570 --> 00:01:09.450
Including plush fox friend, horse friend,
raccoon friend, and even a vermine friend.

00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:12.950
Jeff Highsmith built his son this mission
control desk.

00:01:12.950 --> 00:01:17.189
Featured on the MAKE YouTube channel, it has
a map and a magnetic backing to track the

00:01:17.189 --> 00:01:22.750
spaceships route, a huge control panel of
LED lighted switches, and it recreates real-life

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:25.740
situations from actual NASA missions.

00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:31.119
Such as when the crew of the Apollo 12 mission
was instructed to switch "SCE to AUX" after

00:01:31.119 --> 00:01:32.549
a lightning strike.

00:01:32.549 --> 00:01:33.560
Draw It.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:39.560
Stones and Bones is a series by French Artist
DZO Oliver that uses bone and rock as a canvas.

00:01:39.560 --> 00:01:44.459
When he was out of paper for a short time
he decided to use a different natural material

00:01:44.459 --> 00:01:49.649
and says that the rough, smooth, and absorbent
surfaces made it quite the adventure.

00:01:49.649 --> 00:01:52.560
Also, his paper illustrations are incredible.

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:58.639
Photographer Vesa Lehtimaki uses forced perspective,
baking soda, and lego to create scenes from

00:01:58.639 --> 00:01:59.639
Star Wars.

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:04.710
The lighting, perspective and composition
make the photos incredibly realistic in never

00:02:04.710 --> 00:02:10.440
before seen scenes from the movie like "Last
ship to rendezvous point", "The Backyard Falcon",

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.790
"Snow Troopers Delight", and "Casual Parking."

00:02:13.790 --> 00:02:30.230
And now for the work of Bruce Yan depicting
iconic brands with a pop culture twist.

00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:33.270
Joe Mangrum creates beautiful artwork using
sand.

00:02:33.270 --> 00:02:39.319
He has created over 650 public sand paintings
worldwide since 2009.

00:02:39.319 --> 00:02:45.390
He says the world is divided in so many ways
and he uses his artwork as spontaneous creations

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:49.469
in the streets to act as vibrant catalysts
for social interaction.

